1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,007
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:30,827 --> 00:00:53,393
homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one and I thought I'd sort of try and put things together to make it clear as to what the role of awareness is in the process of enlightenment and what else is necessary so now if we begin with the life of the Buddha himself

3
00:00:53,609 --> 00:00:59,198
remember that he had practiced quite fiercely for six years.

4
00:00:59,978 --> 00:01:01,722
And before that he probably dabbled a bit.

5
00:01:02,942 --> 00:01:15,623
So in the first year or so, let's take a look now, it would be the first year or so, yes, he attains all these very profound absorptions to the point that both teachers ask him to join him as a teacher.

6
00:01:16,984 --> 00:01:18,908
And these are what we now call the jhanas.

7
00:01:22,685 --> 00:01:30,715
Also during that time he's obviously keeping his mind very still because one of the factors of enlightenment, one of the factors of the jhanas is a still mind, a concentrated mind.

8
00:01:33,198 --> 00:01:38,125
Then he does mortification exercises, mainly around not eating really.

9
00:01:39,626 --> 00:01:43,593
And he comes to the end of this process after six years and he's got nowhere.

10
00:01:43,972 --> 00:01:50,802
Nowhere in terms of his koan, in terms of his real life question, which is, is there an end to suffering?

11
00:01:53,278 --> 00:01:56,167
Now all that time, he had awareness.

12
00:02:01,121 --> 00:02:06,376
Now he comes to that point, and in desperation, he's sitting by the roadside looking pretty ragged,

13
00:02:07,487 --> 00:02:11,753
And a woman comes along with a bowl of rice, as you know, meaning to offer it to a god.

14
00:02:11,873 --> 00:02:16,981
In the scriptures, they say that she mistook him for a deva, for an angel, for a god.

15
00:02:17,062 --> 00:02:19,004
But I don't think he looked like that at all.

16
00:02:19,985 --> 00:02:23,350
So they took pity on him and said, you'd better take some of this rice.

17
00:02:24,752 --> 00:02:26,415
So he had this rice, and he felt sort of fulfilled.

18
00:02:26,455 --> 00:02:28,778
And he thought about what was going on and all that.

19
00:02:28,878 --> 00:02:30,901
And he must have been pretty miserable.

20
00:02:31,323 --> 00:02:32,204
His mates had left him.

21
00:02:33,605 --> 00:02:35,688
They said he'd gone soft because he'd eaten his rice.

22
00:02:38,217 --> 00:02:47,044
And then he remembered this little time in childhood, when he is observing his father, he's watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

23
00:02:49,706 --> 00:03:02,498
Now there's something in that observation, there was something in that particular moment, which he remembered at that time, in a time of desperation, looking back over his life, wondering whether there was an end to suffering.

24
00:03:02,519 --> 00:03:04,920
And he remembers this particular state of mind.

25
00:03:06,021 --> 00:03:06,401
See?

26
00:03:07,849 --> 00:03:12,817
If you go back, can you remember a particular state of mind at the age of 8, 9, 10, 12?

27
00:03:15,259 --> 00:03:30,961
So it must have been something that he really remembered, something about the quality of that observation, which he then, of course, goes and sits and determines not to move until his eyes are enlightened or he drops dead.

28
00:03:31,901 --> 00:03:32,742
Have you tried that?

29
00:03:37,381 --> 00:03:43,728
So he sat there, and luckily for him, and for us, he became enlightened.

30
00:03:43,828 --> 00:03:49,834
He had this insight which liberated him, you see, liberated him from this confusion about suffering.

31
00:03:54,818 --> 00:03:56,340
So that's his story.

32
00:03:56,401 --> 00:04:02,747
Then, of course, the whole of his life is actually talking about this moment, of how to get to this moment of liberation.

33
00:04:03,992 --> 00:04:21,959
And the core discourse is on the Satipatthana discourse here, the discourse on how to establish this sati, which we translate as mindfulness, awareness, attention, being present.

34
00:04:21,978 --> 00:04:25,764
All these are about being here in a particular way.

35
00:04:29,692 --> 00:04:33,817
Now, if we look at this, you'll see it's the words he uses, you see.

36
00:04:34,557 --> 00:04:44,009
He says that the meditator sits and he observes these four frames of reference.

37
00:04:44,028 --> 00:04:51,598
The body, feelings, the mind with its emotions, and dhamma, which he means to look at all this from the point of view of his teachings.

38
00:04:52,117 --> 00:04:56,442
The three characteristics, the four noble truths, eight of these, ten of those, and so on.

39
00:04:57,959 --> 00:05:03,869
And he says to do it with atapi, sampajanyo satima.

40
00:05:03,889 --> 00:05:07,576
Now atapi comes from the word tapos, which means mortification exercise.

41
00:05:08,757 --> 00:05:10,982
So in other words, it's real energy.

42
00:05:12,423 --> 00:05:19,916
So those people who translate the Zen effortless effort, meaning that you can just lie down and it'll happen, haven't read this particular discourse.

43
00:05:20,504 --> 00:05:21,906
So there's some energy here.

44
00:05:21,946 --> 00:05:22,826
We need some energy.

45
00:05:23,327 --> 00:05:24,288
We need some commitment.

46
00:05:24,309 --> 00:05:28,494
We need some real putting of our effort behind something.

47
00:05:30,416 --> 00:05:33,740
The word sati-ma is just an adjective from sati.

48
00:05:34,201 --> 00:05:36,745
So, with awareness, translated.

49
00:05:37,064 --> 00:05:37,725
Mindfully.

50
00:05:38,846 --> 00:05:40,889
And the middle word is sampajano.

51
00:05:41,310 --> 00:05:46,377
Sampajano meaning with intelligence.

52
00:05:47,334 --> 00:05:49,017
is intelligent.

53
00:05:49,077 --> 00:05:58,331
These core words are at a constant recurrence throughout the discourse.

54
00:05:58,372 --> 00:06:14,877
When we get into the discourse itself, which describes in more detail how we establish these four frames of reference, the body, feelings in the body, emotional states, mental states, and the Dhamma, we get these recurring phrases.

55
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:46,182
he says to establish mindfulness on one of these four and to do it inwardly just to the point of being able to stay with it then the next stage is to observe the rising and falling that's the next stage and then finally he says to dwell upon it to dwell upon the object of meditation

56
00:06:47,865 --> 00:07:17,653
just so much that jnana and patisati can arise naturally jnana is insight sati is awareness so there's nowhere in the scripture that sati and paññā are separated wherever there's sati there's paññā so now sati is that awareness, general awareness

57
00:07:18,713 --> 00:07:20,536
Paññā is intelligence.

58
00:07:20,555 --> 00:07:24,142
It's an intuitive intelligence.

59
00:07:24,163 --> 00:07:36,564
Now, if we go back to sati, go back to awareness, a robber, in the midst of robbing a bank, is ultra-aware, isn't he?

60
00:07:37,387 --> 00:07:37,766
I'd be.

61
00:07:38,629 --> 00:07:39,230
Very mindful.

62
00:07:40,572 --> 00:07:42,696
My head would be sparking.

63
00:07:44,093 --> 00:07:48,437
When you're crossing a road and it's busy and you've got to watch yourself, you're aware.

64
00:07:49,778 --> 00:07:57,324
So there's something about the awareness which is going to become enlightened, which is leading us to enlightenment, which is not ordinary awareness.

65
00:07:58,286 --> 00:08:02,329
That's why the Buddha calls it samasati, right awareness.

66
00:08:04,892 --> 00:08:05,853
A baby is aware.

67
00:08:05,913 --> 00:08:11,838
In fact, if anything, a child is living almost in a very present moment, but it's not samasati.

68
00:08:14,401 --> 00:08:17,285
So there must be something else to the sati.

69
00:08:18,125 --> 00:08:29,742
Now, if we go now to the factors of enlightenment, then we come across those factors which are necessary to also be there against this background of sati.

70
00:08:30,423 --> 00:08:34,148
So sati, you can say, is like a field of awareness.

71
00:08:34,582 --> 00:08:36,284
It's just a being present.

72
00:08:37,005 --> 00:08:44,494
But there must come something into that presence which is going to spark, which is going to actually see something.

73
00:08:46,096 --> 00:08:56,648
And what we find in the seven factors are this dhamma vichaya, dhamma vichaya, which means investigation of dhamma.

74
00:08:57,349 --> 00:09:01,653
So although we have this awareness, it has to be pointed at something.

75
00:09:01,802 --> 00:09:04,047
It has to be aware of something.

76
00:09:04,067 --> 00:09:06,351
There has to be an intentionality behind it.

77
00:09:07,134 --> 00:09:16,572
You can't just flop, go into this wondrous, spacious state of being all things, in a state of open awareness, because nothing's going to happen.

78
00:09:16,993 --> 00:09:21,802
It's very nice, it's very peaceful, it's very beautiful, but it's dull, it's daft.

79
00:09:23,437 --> 00:09:24,138
Nothing happens.

80
00:09:24,759 --> 00:09:26,620
So there has to come in this Dhammawicca.

81
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:34,410
This Dhammawicca, this investigation of Dhamma, has to be balanced with upeka, with equanimity.

82
00:09:35,171 --> 00:09:40,037
This suggests that this investigation must not have a question there.

83
00:09:42,299 --> 00:09:43,041
That's the problem.

84
00:09:43,422 --> 00:09:47,807
As soon as we say, let's investigate something, a question arises.

85
00:09:48,513 --> 00:10:18,299
somehow we have to we have to develop that curiosity which is just a question mark as soon as there's a word put to it as soon as there's a looking for something then it's going to be corrupted it's going to be corrupted by that concept that you're looking for now balanced with that you have PT and Pasedi PT here translates as interest

86
00:10:19,782 --> 00:10:21,923
Interest is an attitude, isn't it?

87
00:10:24,125 --> 00:10:27,830
It's a mental state to have interest in something.

88
00:10:27,850 --> 00:10:32,153
There's a sort of eagerness included in there, a wanting to know.

89
00:10:32,195 --> 00:10:35,138
It's a heart state to be interested in something.

90
00:10:36,658 --> 00:10:39,841
Now that has to be balanced with passere, which is tranquility.

91
00:10:42,445 --> 00:10:46,548
If interest is not balanced that way, then it becomes excited.

92
00:10:47,845 --> 00:10:53,892
And if there's no interest there, then you enter into this lovely meditative state of tranquility.

93
00:10:54,753 --> 00:10:56,514
So you can see meditators when they do that.

94
00:10:56,754 --> 00:10:57,515
See, they'll be like this.

95
00:11:00,359 --> 00:11:02,100
And if you wake them up, they say, oh, I'm here.

96
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:02,642
What's wrong?

97
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:03,081
I'm aware.

98
00:11:04,124 --> 00:11:04,264
See?

99
00:11:04,744 --> 00:11:06,546
Put them to sleep.

100
00:11:06,566 --> 00:11:06,966
It's lovely.

101
00:11:07,628 --> 00:11:08,428
Nothing's going to happen.

102
00:11:09,028 --> 00:11:13,254
They're going to end up after an hour just as daft as they were before they started.

103
00:11:14,054 --> 00:11:17,599
So there has to be this intelligence, this interest, this wanting to know.

104
00:11:19,131 --> 00:11:28,563
And subsisting all that, subsisting and helping all that, is of course concentration, which is this one pointedness of the mind, the ability of the mind to stay still.

105
00:11:29,705 --> 00:11:39,336
And the effort, and this is the atapi, this is the effort of mortification exercises, is just enough effort to maintain that.

106
00:11:40,077 --> 00:11:43,721
That's all.

107
00:11:45,811 --> 00:11:48,413
So there's your seven factors of enlightenment.

108
00:11:48,453 --> 00:11:50,034
And you can see that in the scriptures.

109
00:11:50,095 --> 00:11:54,620
He never separates awareness from intelligence, awareness from intuition.

110
00:11:55,461 --> 00:12:02,528
So when we meditate and we sit here, the first effort is to bring the mind to a stillness.

111
00:12:03,448 --> 00:12:14,080
But once you're in that stillness, once you've made the effort to, as it were, quiet down and to become aware of the object, there has to arise in us this wanting to know.

112
00:12:15,831 --> 00:12:17,794
Now, what is it we want to know?

113
00:12:17,835 --> 00:12:22,482
What is it that wanting has to be pointed to?

114
00:12:24,206 --> 00:12:30,495
So here, the Buddha simply says to become aware of the three characteristics of existence.

115
00:12:30,515 --> 00:12:38,970
Because when we become aware of the three characteristics of existence, we're undermining this consciousness which believes itself to be a self.

116
00:12:40,991 --> 00:12:45,158
So as long as we are aware of transience, and that's his next step, you see.

117
00:12:45,477 --> 00:12:50,004
So the first step was just to dwell upon the object.

118
00:12:51,306 --> 00:12:54,409
The second step is to become aware of its process.

119
00:12:55,652 --> 00:13:07,067
But here, to my mind, I'm not so sure this is particularly commentarial, but to my mind, this watching of anicca, watching of transiency, includes the other two.

120
00:13:08,144 --> 00:13:14,291
Which is to observe how suffering arises and to observe that quality of not me, not mine.

121
00:13:16,633 --> 00:13:18,294
See, so there are your three characteristics.

122
00:13:21,457 --> 00:13:33,490
So now you can see that this intuitive intelligence which is natural to us and which is the same intelligence that works out how much we have to pay for the bills and what we have to do at work.

123
00:13:33,530 --> 00:13:35,332
It's all the same intelligence.

124
00:13:35,971 --> 00:13:39,677
There's no other intelligence than the intelligence we have.

125
00:13:40,839 --> 00:13:48,591
What we need to do is clarify the intelligence of thought and clarify the intelligence of any distorting emotion.

126
00:13:48,931 --> 00:13:51,315
And we do that by making states of mind objects.

127
00:13:52,437 --> 00:14:01,049
We do that by bringing the mind into the present moment so that thought can't get in because thought is always after thought.

128
00:14:02,818 --> 00:14:06,086
When you're involved in something, there's no room for thought.

129
00:14:07,128 --> 00:14:22,701
So the whole process of the meditation is to bring this, is to, as it were, close down the awareness into the present moment to an object arising and passing away so that there's no time but to see what there is.

130
00:14:24,030 --> 00:14:33,904
But that seeing is guided, is actually being primed to see the three factors, to see the three characteristics of existence.

131
00:14:33,924 --> 00:14:36,006
The fact that it's arising and passing away.

132
00:14:36,607 --> 00:14:38,270
The fact that it's not me, not mine.

133
00:14:38,431 --> 00:14:39,072
The distance.

134
00:14:39,672 --> 00:14:49,566
And the fact that any time I form a relationship with it, of wanting or not wanting, possession or identity, some dissatisfaction arises.

135
00:14:52,009 --> 00:15:18,878
and it's just watching that that liberates this consciousness from wrong relationship to the body mind and heart it's in and that's all we're doing we're just changing our relationship to the world and remember in Buddhist terms in the Buddhist terms the world is how we experience the world in other words it's within this as he says fathom long body it's not outside us it's within this bubble of our consciousness

136
00:15:21,034 --> 00:15:22,118
That's what we've got to change.

137
00:15:31,585 --> 00:15:32,326
So now...

138
00:15:33,370 --> 00:16:02,549
considering his own discovery of the role of awareness which you know when you think about it it can't only have been awareness it must have also been the memory of this intuition that came with it this way of looking and the example that I always use is of a little child who's round about pre-language or around about the beginning of language where there's no conceptual thinking as such they might have a word car whatever but there's nothing built up around it conceptually

139
00:16:03,172 --> 00:16:06,376
And you'll often see them see something like a bug which they've never seen before.

140
00:16:07,097 --> 00:16:08,639
And you see them just lock onto it.

141
00:16:10,562 --> 00:16:11,663
They just lock onto it.

142
00:16:11,924 --> 00:16:13,626
There's no time as far as they're concerned.

143
00:16:13,647 --> 00:16:15,490
There's just this thing crawling away.

144
00:16:16,672 --> 00:16:18,313
And you'll see their mouths drop.

145
00:16:18,533 --> 00:16:21,678
Now when the mouth drops and the tongue relaxes, there's no thought.

146
00:16:24,202 --> 00:16:25,804
So there they are, just in that moment.

147
00:16:25,945 --> 00:16:27,106
And they're just stuck there, you see.

148
00:16:27,486 --> 00:16:30,731
And then some well-meaning parent will tell them to shut their mouth.

149
00:16:31,825 --> 00:16:32,405
and kill it.

150
00:16:33,407 --> 00:16:37,751
But if you leave the kid alone, then of course it comes out of it and says, what is it?

151
00:16:39,333 --> 00:16:40,095
See?

152
00:16:40,115 --> 00:16:43,437
Now once the parent says, oh that's a beetle, that's it, it doesn't look anymore.

153
00:16:44,178 --> 00:16:45,100
It knows it.

154
00:16:45,120 --> 00:16:45,280
See?

155
00:16:45,581 --> 00:16:47,844
And we've lost that direct contact with beetles.

156
00:16:50,086 --> 00:16:51,847
When was the last time you really looked at a beetle?

157
00:16:54,091 --> 00:16:57,333
So that's what conceptual, that's what the concepts do.

158
00:16:57,835 --> 00:17:00,398
They make us presume that

159
00:17:00,495 --> 00:17:06,848
that in seeing a thing through the vision or through the prism of a concept, we actually experience it.

160
00:17:08,672 --> 00:17:16,007
So somehow we've got to go beyond that, and we do that by constantly bringing this attention into the present moment.

161
00:17:16,122 --> 00:17:19,788
And as it locks into the present moment, there can't be room for thought.

162
00:17:19,808 --> 00:17:21,833
And we're right there with that childlike mind.

163
00:17:22,594 --> 00:17:30,308
Except this time, it actually has some intelligence, some stored wisdom behind it, which the child doesn't have.

164
00:17:30,910 --> 00:17:33,674
If the child had that, it'd become enlightened at the age of three.

165
00:17:34,532 --> 00:17:43,989
But we have to go through the horror of our lives in order to build up the wisdom of how to develop this way of looking.

166
00:17:44,430 --> 00:17:47,134
Remember, it's suffering which leads us to the enlightenment.

167
00:17:49,357 --> 00:17:53,546
So we've got to go through the pain, or else there's no gain.

168
00:17:53,605 --> 00:17:54,988
Everybody knows that.

169
00:17:57,601 --> 00:18:00,965
So in this scripture, you see, he's very clear about that.

170
00:18:01,467 --> 00:18:08,277
So now we come to this confusion as to how we can be confused with the different traditions.

171
00:18:09,439 --> 00:18:17,790
So as far as my understanding is, and you're welcome to correct me after the talk, there are two major traditions.

172
00:18:18,192 --> 00:18:22,317
There's the Vipassana tradition and there's the Dzogchen Zazen tradition.

173
00:18:22,337 --> 00:18:25,583
And just on the outside of that, there's the Koan tradition.

174
00:18:26,811 --> 00:18:33,760
So now, what is the difference between those two approaches which can cause confusion to meditators?

175
00:18:38,287 --> 00:18:47,980
In the vipassana process, we want to get to that satipanya, we want to get to that sampajanio satima.

176
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:53,426
And we do it by way of using an object within the body, the breath itself,

177
00:18:54,907 --> 00:19:08,801
By turning inward and going into the breath, we pull out that singular object and we begin to, as it were, bury our awareness and that intuitive intelligence just into a single sensation.

178
00:19:10,506 --> 00:19:12,089
All the world is in a grain of sand.

179
00:19:13,758 --> 00:19:32,744
In that moment, you see, when we, as it were, open up to the field of awareness, so that we're not just concentrated into the breath, but able to observe anything which draws our attention, we're not looking for anything, so I'm sitting watching the breath and there's a bird song,

180
00:19:33,721 --> 00:19:36,424
And it's the bird song which is drawing my attention.

181
00:19:37,425 --> 00:19:38,928
I'm not looking for bird songs.

182
00:19:39,669 --> 00:19:46,037
And as I go to the ear, as I go to the ear base, I'm interested in the process of hearing.

183
00:19:46,076 --> 00:19:47,019
I'm not interested in the bird.

184
00:19:48,019 --> 00:19:49,962
I'll see the image of the bird in my mind.

185
00:19:50,022 --> 00:19:53,326
I hear and I feel my response to it.

186
00:19:53,586 --> 00:19:57,011
So I can see this whole connection I have with the outside world.

187
00:19:58,138 --> 00:20:02,285
I can see that when the bird stops, there's a longing for Tahir to go on a little bit more.

188
00:20:02,846 --> 00:20:04,689
So there's my attachment.

189
00:20:05,410 --> 00:20:05,651
You see?

190
00:20:06,392 --> 00:20:07,472
So that's what I'm interested in.

191
00:20:07,512 --> 00:20:13,702
I'm interested in the way that this mind is constantly wandering between wanting and not wanting.

192
00:20:14,723 --> 00:20:16,326
How things arise and pass away.

193
00:20:16,807 --> 00:20:19,571
Creating that distance, recognizing it's not me, not mine.

194
00:20:20,653 --> 00:20:26,221
And it's all come from this center in the breath where I've honed the seven factors of enlightenment.

195
00:20:28,717 --> 00:20:36,968
Now, if you go to the Dzogchen school, or the Zazen school, the Zazen school I know personally, as soon as you sit, you're supposed to be there.

196
00:20:38,128 --> 00:20:38,490
Like that.

197
00:20:38,911 --> 00:20:39,290
Boom, boom.

198
00:20:39,692 --> 00:20:40,132
You made it.

199
00:20:40,653 --> 00:20:41,513
That's it.

200
00:20:42,015 --> 00:20:42,575
You're right there.

201
00:20:42,654 --> 00:20:48,423
Just where you were, it took these poor Vipassana ninis weeks to get there.

202
00:20:49,183 --> 00:20:52,107
These Dzogchen guys, boom, that's it, they're there.

203
00:20:53,741 --> 00:20:54,722
See?

204
00:20:54,742 --> 00:20:56,204
Now it can't be so, can it?

205
00:20:56,346 --> 00:20:57,426
There must be something going on.

206
00:20:57,747 --> 00:21:03,855
So that somebody who throws themselves into a Zazen position, Shikantaza, you know.

207
00:21:05,678 --> 00:21:10,724
So now when you look at their training, you can see how they get there and are able to hold it.

208
00:21:10,944 --> 00:21:16,813
Remember that in most, like, something like Sogyal Rinpoche, as far as I know, you sit in Dzogchen for ten minutes.

209
00:21:18,228 --> 00:21:23,913
That's all they can expect from somebody who's doing their practice at an ordinary level.

210
00:21:25,134 --> 00:21:27,738
Now remember that insight in the Enlightenment doesn't take any time.

211
00:21:28,719 --> 00:21:30,140
You either see it or you don't.

212
00:21:30,160 --> 00:21:31,461
It's a flash, that's it, it's finished.

213
00:21:33,462 --> 00:21:39,609
But if we look at the whole tradition, then we see how they can just sit there for ten minutes, or maybe an hour, or whatever.

214
00:21:41,592 --> 00:21:43,133
Hundred thousand bows.

215
00:21:44,394 --> 00:21:45,536
Om Mani Padme Hum.

216
00:21:45,915 --> 00:21:47,037
Days on end.

217
00:21:48,130 --> 00:21:49,292
See, what are those practices?

218
00:21:50,295 --> 00:21:52,599
Visualizations, purifying the heart.

219
00:21:54,565 --> 00:21:54,805
See?

220
00:21:55,246 --> 00:22:00,679
It's only when you've been through all that can you throw yourself on the cushion and enter into Dzogchen.

221
00:22:03,164 --> 00:22:04,688
There's the balance of the practice.

222
00:22:05,865 --> 00:22:29,951
Dzogchen masters and Zazen masters will tell you that the error of somebody in Dzogchen and Zazen is that they fall into the same error as Vipassana people to move into that state of clear awareness, absolute body, straight, perfect energy, no intelligence.

223
00:22:29,971 --> 00:22:32,413
Perfect peace and happiness until they wake up.

224
00:22:36,140 --> 00:22:39,387
If you look at the Zazen school, you've only got to go up to Throstle Hole.

225
00:22:39,890 --> 00:22:41,012
It's been years since I went there.

226
00:22:41,894 --> 00:22:48,992
But when I used to go up there, you'd work three hours at a shop.

227
00:22:49,193 --> 00:22:49,835
You'd never stop.

228
00:22:50,576 --> 00:22:51,599
And you worked fast.

229
00:22:53,655 --> 00:23:03,771
I remember once I was saying to the work chiefs today, the abbot wanted soil moved from one end to the other end to build a little garden.

230
00:23:04,452 --> 00:23:14,087
So I was stood at one end with a spade, and there was another guy stood at the other end, and there was this Dominican priest with a wheelbarrow, belting up and down.

231
00:23:14,868 --> 00:23:17,373
He shoved it in and down, he chucked it out and back up.

232
00:23:17,653 --> 00:23:18,414
Three hours!

233
00:23:22,748 --> 00:23:24,069
Weeding for three hours.

234
00:23:28,096 --> 00:23:33,345
The whole idea of that Zazen meditation is not something separate from what you do.

235
00:23:33,365 --> 00:23:43,119
It's a common mistake, especially in the Vipassana, because we have these special practices, special occasions, but in Zen they always talk about ordinary daily life.

236
00:23:44,990 --> 00:23:47,493
So there you are weeding, and you're weeding.

237
00:23:47,694 --> 00:23:48,737
You're putting your mind in it.

238
00:23:48,817 --> 00:23:52,522
You know, when you wash, you've heard these Zen sayings, when you wash the pots, just wash the pots.

239
00:23:53,144 --> 00:23:54,507
So when you weed, you weed, you see.

240
00:23:54,948 --> 00:23:58,453
And you're weeding, and you get into the rhythm of weeding, and you don't want to leave the weeding.

241
00:23:59,134 --> 00:24:00,637
And the bell goes, and you want to keep weeding.

242
00:24:01,038 --> 00:24:04,964
See, and then you go back, and you're full of this energy.

243
00:24:05,987 --> 00:24:08,330
And you go, boom, something's going to go, and you're there, you see.

244
00:24:09,442 --> 00:24:17,151
It's not that the mind doesn't wander, but at least you've got some concentration because of the hard work, you've got the energy, and so you can sit in zazen, just sitting.

245
00:24:19,954 --> 00:24:20,075
See?

246
00:24:24,259 --> 00:24:37,997
Now the koan is an interesting one, because the koan actually has its roots, all these things have its roots in the fundamental schools of Theravada and for the Mahayana, what became known as the Sarvastavadin school.

247
00:24:39,022 --> 00:25:04,440
If you have a look at this very dry tome called the Path of Purification by Buddha Gosar, a scholar of the medieval ages, the driest book in the world, bag of bones, but probably the most brilliant piece of, most brilliant compendium of spiritual exercises you'll come across.

248
00:25:05,517 --> 00:25:09,794
And one of them is how to become enlightened by repeating the word death.

249
00:25:13,509 --> 00:25:15,155
How to become enlightened by repeating the word death.

250
00:25:15,827 --> 00:25:18,270
So now, how are we supposed to do that, you see?

251
00:25:18,891 --> 00:25:26,398
Well, the idea is that you sit, you be silent, and you use the word death to contact your feelings about death.

252
00:25:27,200 --> 00:25:30,063
Every time you say death, images may come, feelings may come.

253
00:25:30,442 --> 00:25:40,012
It's an internalised practice of what's in the Satipatthana Sutta, known as looking at dead bodies in cemeteries.

254
00:25:41,258 --> 00:25:43,922
It's the asubar, it's the horrible meditations.

255
00:25:44,502 --> 00:25:52,455
And you're supposed to go to a cemetery and a charnel ground where the bodies were just left, you know, and eaten by vultures and rotting and all that, rats around.

256
00:25:52,796 --> 00:25:57,523
And you're supposed to sit there and just watch bodies rotting, see?

257
00:25:57,584 --> 00:26:02,711
Come back, see them in different states and keep saying to yourself, just as this body is, so mine will be.

258
00:26:05,777 --> 00:26:08,801
The commentary warns you to not to sit windward.

259
00:26:10,739 --> 00:26:11,599
Very detailed.

260
00:26:13,042 --> 00:26:18,771
So there you are sitting, repeating this word death, and it's bringing up all your emotions about it, all your feelings about death.

261
00:26:19,393 --> 00:26:21,596
And just like Indra Pasana you observe in part one.

262
00:26:22,238 --> 00:26:23,099
And who is it?

263
00:26:23,359 --> 00:26:24,801
What is it that's afraid of death?

264
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:27,125
It's the self, isn't it?

265
00:26:28,367 --> 00:26:30,952
So once you've cut through the fear of death, what is it to be afraid of?

266
00:26:33,016 --> 00:26:34,198
Hence the Enlightenment.

267
00:26:34,786 --> 00:26:45,588
now from that you can see how the koans came you see the koans now the regular koan in somewhere like Korea is who am I or what is it

268
00:26:46,311 --> 00:26:53,842
Now, a person in the old days would have been given a koan, and they would have been caught up in this intellectual answer.

269
00:26:53,981 --> 00:26:59,209
The Rinzai school was meant for, was supposed to be for samurais, right, and for the intellectuals.

270
00:26:59,788 --> 00:27:11,964
So, the yogi would come along, and the master would say, would ask him the koan, you see, and he'd wait for the answer, and the guy would give him some sort of explanation, well, I'm not this, I'm not, and he'd get a clout across the ear.

271
00:27:12,366 --> 00:27:16,835
And he'd keep coming, getting bonked on the head, until finally he stopped thinking.

272
00:27:17,957 --> 00:27:18,518
That's the point.

273
00:27:18,617 --> 00:27:20,461
That's the point of the koan, to stop thinking.

274
00:27:21,061 --> 00:27:25,971
So the idea in the koan when we say something like, who am I?

275
00:27:25,990 --> 00:27:29,597
And remember, these koans come up naturally in your meditation.

276
00:27:29,617 --> 00:27:35,387
Just feeling a feeling and hearing a little question like, what is this?

277
00:27:35,748 --> 00:27:36,670
That's your koan.

278
00:27:37,442 --> 00:27:40,967
is turning on that intelligence.

279
00:27:41,186 --> 00:27:42,108
That's what the Quran is doing.

280
00:27:42,128 --> 00:27:48,855
It's turning on that intelligence, making that intelligence look in a certain way, but beyond thought.

281
00:27:50,117 --> 00:27:55,263
So the meditator, just like one would say, death, and just feel what comes up, you might say, who am I?

282
00:27:55,584 --> 00:28:00,549
And just rest in that moment and let the intelligence take over.

283
00:28:00,569 --> 00:28:02,893
Our problem is we keep getting in the way.

284
00:28:02,958 --> 00:28:08,366
After all, we keep trying to manipulate that intelligence to see what we want it to see and become enlightened.

285
00:28:11,551 --> 00:28:21,808
So you can see how the koan is just an extension, is just a more obvious way of exciting this panya, this intuitive intelligence we have within us.

286
00:28:24,032 --> 00:28:26,636
So now you can see, if you come from the Zen tradition,

287
00:28:27,088 --> 00:28:30,653
And you meet a Theravadin, and the Theravada says, all you need is awareness.

288
00:28:30,673 --> 00:28:32,736
They'll say, oh, no, no, no, that won't do at all.

289
00:28:34,718 --> 00:28:40,565
But in the Theravada understanding, whenever you say right awareness, the intelligence is included.

290
00:28:41,306 --> 00:28:47,752
It's not right awareness unless the intelligence is being activated, the intuitive intelligence.

291
00:28:49,295 --> 00:28:54,260
And that's where the confusion lies often when you meet these schools, because they're coming from slightly different traditions.

292
00:28:54,493 --> 00:28:55,434
But it's always the same.

293
00:28:55,836 --> 00:28:56,576
It's always the same.

294
00:28:57,377 --> 00:29:21,295
And in his book, which is still considered to be a classic of meditation, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation by Jnana Poniketera, a very famous German monk who died not so long ago, he said that there was a time when people thought that Theravada meditation, Vipassana, and Zen were sort of two opposites, you know, belonged to two different worlds.

295
00:29:21,798 --> 00:29:33,198
But in fact, when these teachers came together, and when people who had practiced both actually began to realize that in fact it's all one and the same thing.

296
00:29:34,240 --> 00:29:36,223
And when you think about it, how else could it be?

297
00:29:37,226 --> 00:29:37,967
How else could it be?

298
00:29:45,507 --> 00:29:47,130
So there we have it, you see.

299
00:29:47,810 --> 00:29:53,361
The Buddha's own remembrance in childhood of a particular level of consciousness.

300
00:29:53,421 --> 00:29:54,522
It's not a state of mind.

301
00:29:54,563 --> 00:29:55,785
It's not an emotional state.

302
00:29:55,805 --> 00:29:56,686
It's not a thought state.

303
00:29:57,769 --> 00:30:00,252
It's a way of seeing things.

304
00:30:02,978 --> 00:30:06,625
Because of his own practice, he has that concentration of mind.

305
00:30:07,286 --> 00:30:08,126
He has the effort.

306
00:30:08,969 --> 00:30:10,131
And he has the rice pudding.

307
00:30:11,359 --> 00:30:13,883
And he sits under the tree and he becomes enlightened.

308
00:30:14,403 --> 00:30:18,007
And then he realizes what the factors are that made him get there.

309
00:30:19,548 --> 00:30:22,271
And the main factor is this sati.

310
00:30:23,413 --> 00:30:25,955
Behind it there are all the faculties.

311
00:30:25,976 --> 00:30:27,557
Why does he put sati first?

312
00:30:27,938 --> 00:30:31,520
Because that's your main disposition, awareness.

313
00:30:33,443 --> 00:30:37,688
To begin with the awareness of the object is your disposition.

314
00:30:38,308 --> 00:30:43,854
And then once the awareness is there, the concentration and effort will come to rise to support it.

315
00:30:44,575 --> 00:31:01,309
And once the awareness and concentration is there, and it's coming more and more into the present moment, the intuitive wisdom, supported by faith, if there's any scepticism you've had it, supported by faith, uses those qualities to see clearly what's going on.

316
00:31:03,551 --> 00:31:06,595
And just that seeing is its own liberation.

317
00:31:09,410 --> 00:31:15,297
So the liberation is consciousness liberating itself from wrong view.

318
00:31:16,838 --> 00:31:20,663
And the whole process of the enlightenment is simply to get out of the way.

319
00:31:23,126 --> 00:31:23,968
The effortless effort.

320
00:31:36,384 --> 00:31:36,784
That's it.

321
00:31:39,885 --> 00:31:40,887
Is there any questions?

322
00:31:41,208 --> 00:31:42,430
Observations?

323
00:31:42,450 --> 00:31:42,990
Criticism?

324
00:31:44,913 --> 00:31:45,394
Additions?

325
00:31:46,596 --> 00:31:47,258
Editorials?

326
00:31:48,861 --> 00:31:51,526
Yes?

327
00:31:51,546 --> 00:32:06,130
There are many stories about people who follow the teachers and then are severely treated in order to get rid of this ego which you mentioned in the classic.

328
00:32:08,606 --> 00:32:23,825
that is one of the biggest barriers to being able to have these states come together in the right portions and go forward.

329
00:32:26,327 --> 00:32:32,556
How does it terrify you, doing that, you know, going out and scourging yourself on weekends?

330
00:32:35,674 --> 00:32:40,462
I don't think Buddhist teachers were particularly cruel.

331
00:32:40,722 --> 00:32:50,218
I mean, the only real stories come from the Zen tradition where they chop your hand off or something, or chop your finger off if you happen to.

332
00:32:50,238 --> 00:32:50,478
Who?

333
00:32:52,300 --> 00:32:53,303
Oh, yes, yes, yes.

334
00:32:54,704 --> 00:33:02,356
Well, remember that the way teachers teach their students is very much dependent upon the culture.

335
00:33:10,842 --> 00:33:16,211
I mean, I can't imagine a Westerner sort of taking that sort of business.

336
00:33:16,270 --> 00:33:20,479
I mean, they'd probably smack the guy, smack the person back.

337
00:33:22,321 --> 00:33:25,027
It's not within our culture to be battered towards the Enlightenment.

338
00:33:28,953 --> 00:33:30,236
I mean, the Buddha himself wasn't.

339
00:33:31,498 --> 00:33:34,403
Nobody sort of gave him a whack or two.

340
00:33:37,505 --> 00:33:44,472
As Buddhism spreads, remember, it does pick up the culture.

341
00:33:45,974 --> 00:33:59,731
In the West, we're in very early days, very early days, and I can well imagine within two or three generations, four generations, that the Buddhism in the West is remarkably different from the Buddhism elsewhere.

342
00:34:00,393 --> 00:34:01,733
Because that's what's happened everywhere else.

343
00:34:01,814 --> 00:34:06,599
Chinese Buddhism is remarkably different from Japanese, from Thai, from...

344
00:34:06,579 --> 00:34:29,820
from Tibetan so it changes but your core question is in fact how to get rid of ego and the self one of the things that is very difficult for us is the word obedience is the word submission

345
00:34:31,166 --> 00:34:32,208
We can't handle that.

346
00:34:32,289 --> 00:34:37,094
It goes against the whole post-modern idea that I do my own thing in my own way in my own time.

347
00:34:38,998 --> 00:34:47,068
But before the Buddha became enlightened, so it is said, he put his bowl into the river and it flowed upwards against the stream.

348
00:34:48,891 --> 00:34:50,353
Only dead fish go with the flow.

349
00:34:53,597 --> 00:35:00,206
So this was symbolic of the fact that whatever we do towards enlightenment is always going to go against the self.

350
00:35:00,226 --> 00:35:00,666
Always.

351
00:35:00,746 --> 00:35:00,887
Always.

352
00:35:01,929 --> 00:35:20,427
so the self-remember is caught up in a game it's caught up in a game with the world of wanting and not wanting and it finds a certain pleasure there it finds a certain comfort it doesn't want to let go of it because it always thinks if it can get it right it will definitely be perfectly happy

353
00:35:25,014 --> 00:35:55,021
so that's one of the things about bowing people hate to bow but in fact bowing is the physical it's the bodily expression of that submission that's one reason it's the physical expression of submitting yourself to the diktats of the Dharma so if the Dharma says you shouldn't indulge in this then you have to bow to that

354
00:35:56,217 --> 00:36:02,523
If you can't bow to it, if you can't take the teaching, if you can't do it, then you just end up with a very stiff back.

355
00:36:05,086 --> 00:36:08,369
An arthritic back.

356
00:36:09,351 --> 00:36:16,818
And this is one of the fundamental attitudes of any spiritual life.

357
00:36:16,878 --> 00:36:18,521
It's not just Buddhism.

358
00:36:18,541 --> 00:36:20,003
Humility goes all the way through.

359
00:36:20,043 --> 00:36:24,907
This word humility, which has now been downgraded into slavery, you know.

360
00:36:25,867 --> 00:36:28,329
But humility is that ability to be obedient.

361
00:36:29,711 --> 00:36:31,253
Who uses the word obedient these days?

362
00:36:31,893 --> 00:36:33,275
You don't hear parents use it with kids.

363
00:36:33,655 --> 00:36:34,237
Be obedient.

364
00:36:36,519 --> 00:36:39,362
It's all gone out of the language.

365
00:36:39,382 --> 00:36:40,625
It's too painful for the ego.

366
00:36:44,690 --> 00:36:45,570
The word discipline.

367
00:36:46,952 --> 00:36:48,094
The word discipline.

368
00:36:48,918 --> 00:36:55,211
I mean, it actually means, if I remember rightly, study, isn't it?

369
00:36:56,213 --> 00:36:56,936
Disciplina.

370
00:36:57,677 --> 00:36:58,117
Does anybody know?

371
00:36:59,782 --> 00:37:00,322
Disciplina.

372
00:37:00,543 --> 00:37:02,869
It means learning.

373
00:37:05,514 --> 00:37:05,695
Learning.

374
00:37:09,876 --> 00:37:11,820
So in a university you have a discipline.

375
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:21,659
We talk about a discipline, you see, because to study, to advance in knowledge, there has to be this commitment, this order, this discipline.

376
00:37:23,782 --> 00:37:27,969
But these days, education is much more concerned with entertainment.

377
00:37:35,577 --> 00:37:46,273
So, in answer to your question about the way teachers teach, it's often to humble, to humble the student.

378
00:37:46,652 --> 00:37:55,827
I remember when I was in Burma, and I was, you know, being the westerner, and frankly, I just got fed up of bowing to this monk.

379
00:37:56,568 --> 00:37:58,309
I mean, he was my teacher, but I just got fed up with him.

380
00:37:59,512 --> 00:38:02,175
And he was so conceited, as far as I could see.

381
00:38:02,416 --> 00:38:03,818
Arrogant.

382
00:38:03,838 --> 00:38:04,960
I wasn't going to bow to him.

383
00:38:05,563 --> 00:38:07,708
And I remember approaching him and just sitting there.

384
00:38:08,369 --> 00:38:15,641
And he went... And if I hadn't have bowed, I'd have been out.

385
00:38:15,661 --> 00:38:15,981
That's it.

386
00:38:16,483 --> 00:38:16,862
Forget it.

387
00:38:18,405 --> 00:38:22,934
And what he's teaching me is, look, if you're going to take my message, then you'd better have the right attitude.

388
00:38:26,099 --> 00:38:27,842
One of the most painful times of my life.

389
00:38:40,342 --> 00:38:51,137
is the awareness with interest and energy what exactly do you mean by energy?

390
00:38:51,157 --> 00:39:09,101
energy is just the effort to maintain it I mean as a physical thing the only energy you need to become enlightened if we could hold it there the Buddha says for seven years if you're unlucky for seven days if you're really with it it's just the energy to keep you upright

391
00:39:10,516 --> 00:39:11,556
Just the energy in the spine.

392
00:39:13,099 --> 00:39:19,548
So all the energy you need is the resolution, the energy to just keep observing the object.

393
00:39:20,931 --> 00:39:32,726
So that's why I mentioned to those of you here for the meditation that if we are serial meditators, then every time we come to sit, you really have to remind yourself what you're going to do.

394
00:39:33,802 --> 00:39:35,467
And so you make that resolution.

395
00:39:36,007 --> 00:39:41,199
This period of time, I'm going to commit myself to establishing mindfulness.

396
00:39:41,579 --> 00:39:42,641
You know, put it in your own way.

397
00:39:42,702 --> 00:39:51,440
Unless you forget, and you just sit there, it becomes habitual, and the mind wanders, and sure, you've planned your holiday down to America, but I mean, what's the point?

398
00:39:53,362 --> 00:40:01,056
But if you sit and you make this resolution right at the beginning of your sit, then I think you'll find that when you wander, you'll come back to that same resolution.

399
00:40:01,356 --> 00:40:08,510
Because remember, that resolution is conditioning your mind, it's conditioning you to be present.

400
00:40:08,530 --> 00:40:12,838
It's an attitude, it's an attitudinal change to be present.

401
00:40:14,422 --> 00:40:20,806
And I would say that every time you lose it on a dream side, you come back, you stop for a moment, you recognize what's happened, right?

402
00:40:21,768 --> 00:40:24,490
And you recommit yourself with real resolution.

403
00:40:26,132 --> 00:40:27,213
Resolute resolution.

404
00:40:28,673 --> 00:40:34,458
But don't you need like a free flow of energy so no tension?

405
00:40:34,498 --> 00:40:34,958
Say that again?

406
00:40:34,978 --> 00:40:36,219
A free flow of energy so...

407
00:40:36,581 --> 00:40:38,922
In the whole body, not just a resolution.

408
00:40:41,364 --> 00:40:44,007
I don't quite know... Well, should...

409
00:40:44,947 --> 00:41:11,748
yeah oh energy yeah say no more the thing is once you're in this posture and you're lifting the energy up the spine just by sitting tall you see then you're actually correcting all the energy in your body

410
00:41:13,483 --> 00:41:16,626
You will feel, I'm sure many of you have felt, all the chakras fire.

411
00:41:17,288 --> 00:41:20,552
Pain in your stomach, pain in your chest, around your neck, it's all blocked.

412
00:41:20,572 --> 00:41:20,972
That's it.

413
00:41:21,612 --> 00:41:24,235
You don't have to do any yoga posture to become enlightened.

414
00:41:30,081 --> 00:41:30,983
You don't need astrology.

415
00:41:34,206 --> 00:41:34,586
Sorry.

416
00:41:36,668 --> 00:41:41,313
You seem to be saying in the talk that

417
00:41:52,027 --> 00:41:53,168
Is that what you were saying?

418
00:41:53,188 --> 00:41:53,769
That's right.

419
00:41:55,291 --> 00:42:05,286
It seems that people can have quite deep insights into those three experiences, but not have a final cessation in suffering.

420
00:42:05,306 --> 00:42:17,125
Maybe some change in ways that can happen, so they can bring wisdom and intelligence, but there's still a sufferer and still suffering can take place.

421
00:42:17,184 --> 00:42:17,405
Yeah.

422
00:42:18,527 --> 00:42:19,148
So...

423
00:42:25,135 --> 00:42:29,041
Insight or...

424
00:42:29,061 --> 00:42:32,807
It's... Yeah, no, it's...

425
00:42:32,847 --> 00:42:42,324
The insights into these things are like little... Little corrections of view.

426
00:42:43,385 --> 00:42:44,288
Little corrections.

427
00:42:45,208 --> 00:42:49,235
Until the whole thing becomes properly corrected and then you're enlightened.

428
00:42:49,739 --> 00:42:51,521
They're just little adjustments.

429
00:42:52,041 --> 00:42:59,867
And they show up in little changes in the way you behave, in the way you react to similar situations, in the way you don't react to similar situations.

430
00:42:59,887 --> 00:43:01,068
Little changes within you.

431
00:43:02,190 --> 00:43:03,471
It's a very slow process.

432
00:43:03,510 --> 00:43:07,173
I mean, the Buddha often warns us this is a slow process.

433
00:43:09,715 --> 00:43:15,081
And then there are kernel points when we can talk about a shift in perception.

434
00:43:15,221 --> 00:43:19,644
And these are what we call the stream entrant, the non-returner, and the arahat.

435
00:43:20,164 --> 00:43:22,447
I liken it to a stick.

436
00:43:22,827 --> 00:43:24,168
You see, you keep bending the stick.

437
00:43:24,188 --> 00:43:27,413
Now you'll notice that when you first start bending a stick, it's easy, isn't it?

438
00:43:27,994 --> 00:43:29,355
So when you first sit, it's easy.

439
00:43:29,735 --> 00:43:31,838
But as you keep going, you see, you get the resistance.

440
00:43:32,418 --> 00:43:33,659
You get the resistance.

441
00:43:34,360 --> 00:43:36,963
And you get the resistance, you see, and that's the ego, it's pulling away, you see.

442
00:43:37,264 --> 00:43:38,184
And you've just got to keep working.

443
00:43:38,304 --> 00:43:41,527
And sometimes you relax, and you back up again, you see.

444
00:43:42,369 --> 00:43:45,733
But remember that every time you flex it, you are getting stronger.

445
00:43:46,320 --> 00:43:47,682
You all do these exercises, I'm sure.

446
00:43:48,143 --> 00:43:51,007
And then one day, jack!

447
00:43:51,608 --> 00:43:51,849
See?

448
00:43:52,010 --> 00:43:52,451
Two sticks.

449
00:43:52,990 --> 00:43:53,552
Different state.

450
00:43:58,981 --> 00:43:59,081
Yeah.

451
00:43:59,101 --> 00:43:59,641
That's how it goes.

452
00:44:03,146 --> 00:44:04,548
Yes?

453
00:44:04,568 --> 00:44:10,117
My question was going to be that once the stick is broken, is there no going back?

454
00:44:10,637 --> 00:44:12,360
Definitely not.

455
00:44:12,380 --> 00:44:13,282
And who'd want to go back?

456
00:44:13,902 --> 00:44:22,554
You see, if you think of the shift of consciousness, this very great shift that we go through between six and eight, where we get real.

457
00:44:23,815 --> 00:44:31,987
When we're six, believing Father Christmas comes down the chimney is not a problem, because what I can imagine is true, it's fact.

458
00:44:33,369 --> 00:44:35,311
Eight is a bit difficult.

459
00:44:35,443 --> 00:44:37,646
And then this morality comes in.

460
00:44:37,686 --> 00:44:44,215
It's not as though that young children don't feel shame and guilt, but it becomes much more clear around the age of seven, right and wrong.

461
00:44:44,536 --> 00:44:47,541
The tree of the fruit of good and evil.

462
00:44:50,164 --> 00:44:51,606
Now you wouldn't want to go back to three years old.

463
00:44:52,128 --> 00:44:52,688
I don't think so.

464
00:44:54,771 --> 00:45:00,760
So once you've moved, once you've become a sotapanna, once you've become a stream entrant or an arahat, you don't want to go down again.

465
00:45:02,545 --> 00:45:19,389
Is enlightenment a one thing from which there is no going back or is it also a temporary insight?

466
00:45:19,775 --> 00:45:24,543
Now actually, now it's a good question because this is also very confusing from the different traditions.

467
00:45:26,887 --> 00:45:31,998
In Theravadi we have things like jnanas, these insights of vipassana.

468
00:45:32,018 --> 00:45:38,610
In the Japanese tradition we hear about satori and kensho and now they're actually all the same thing you see.

469
00:45:39,652 --> 00:45:46,099
you'll find that when you read the literature and you go through all the traditions and all that, you'll find they're always talking about the same thing.

470
00:45:46,300 --> 00:45:54,849
They're always talking about little insights concerning the three facts, concerning the three characteristics.

471
00:45:54,869 --> 00:45:58,032
Transience, how suffering arises, and not self.

472
00:45:58,052 --> 00:45:58,592
It's always that.

473
00:45:59,094 --> 00:46:08,023
And then you'll see that they often have a special word for what we would call stream entrance, etc., etc.,

474
00:46:08,594 --> 00:46:13,260
Now, up until that stick snaps, you can always go back.

475
00:46:15,784 --> 00:46:17,567
And it's very difficult.

476
00:46:18,889 --> 00:46:19,750
It really is.

477
00:46:19,809 --> 00:46:26,400
Oh, it's soul destroying to have got the stick there and to have given up.

478
00:46:26,420 --> 00:46:32,188
It's like climbing up the mountain and you're almost at the peak and you tumble all the way down.

479
00:46:33,619 --> 00:46:40,009
So it's very important not to push ourselves too much so that in a sense we exhaust ourselves.

480
00:46:40,710 --> 00:46:45,036
We have to take a pace which is our personal pace of enlightenment.

481
00:46:45,356 --> 00:46:46,557
Just our personal pace.

482
00:46:46,918 --> 00:46:53,108
Some people walk round and round and round spiralling up the mountain and the occasional person can just straight up.

483
00:46:54,009 --> 00:46:55,190
So we've all got our little way.

484
00:46:55,451 --> 00:47:00,217
And you have to be very careful that you don't push yourself too much because that would be the error of westerners.

485
00:47:01,952 --> 00:47:10,706
Even if you're only moving at one nanometer per ten years, that's okay, it's moving up.

486
00:47:14,572 --> 00:47:15,494
I'm very careful of that.

487
00:47:16,876 --> 00:47:17,416
Very careful.

488
00:47:18,378 --> 00:47:21,123
And the other mistake, of course, is to overestimate.

489
00:47:21,143 --> 00:47:23,226
I mean, that's the other side, where you think you've made it.

490
00:47:24,106 --> 00:47:27,893
That can be very depressing when you find out that you haven't.

491
00:47:32,277 --> 00:47:38,407
I've had two experiences, just personal experiences, where, I don't know, it was just a pain, really.

492
00:47:39,369 --> 00:47:42,695
And I just came to a point where I thought, God, no, I can't handle this.

493
00:47:42,715 --> 00:47:49,407
And I was just going to cut out and get back to a bit of happiness, for God's sake.

494
00:47:50,047 --> 00:47:55,413
And I just, it was one of these little moments in your spiritual life.

495
00:47:55,913 --> 00:47:57,614
And I actually made a decision to give up.

496
00:47:57,916 --> 00:48:05,204
And all I can say was that the next moment I was filled with an intense horror as to what that meant.

497
00:48:06,184 --> 00:48:19,159
Absolutely, the horror was so awful within me as to what that actually meant that I just went and sat on the cushion and waited until the intention to meditate came again.

498
00:48:20,623 --> 00:48:28,742
And I've also had the experience of thinking you've achieved something and actually you haven't.

499
00:48:29,304 --> 00:48:30,547
That's a bit depressing.

500
00:48:31,610 --> 00:48:33,153
It takes a couple of beers to get over that.

501
00:48:33,795 --> 00:48:38,346
And then you gather energy and you start off again.

502
00:48:45,228 --> 00:49:07,190
The ego gets more and more subtle the more you chase it.

503
00:49:09,713 --> 00:49:13,496
The more you overcome ego, the more subtle it becomes.

504
00:49:14,454 --> 00:49:17,498
Remember, conceit stays with you to the bitter end.

505
00:49:19,842 --> 00:49:22,065
It's the last fetter to go, one of the last fetters.

506
00:49:23,427 --> 00:49:25,329
Restlessness is one of the last fetters.

507
00:49:25,610 --> 00:49:35,423
And restlessness here suggests every neurosis you can think of, but extraordinarily refined.

508
00:49:37,206 --> 00:49:38,487
But it's still there.

509
00:49:39,615 --> 00:49:41,518
So the fear's still there, the anger's still there.

510
00:49:41,538 --> 00:49:43,981
Everything's still there, but it's just like a...

511
00:49:44,001 --> 00:49:45,862
But it's still there, right to the bitter end.

512
00:49:59,239 --> 00:50:01,141
It's a little bit more fun showing things at your own pace.

513
00:50:01,161 --> 00:50:06,768
How do you know if you're being lazy or not trying hardly at all?

514
00:50:06,788 --> 00:50:07,108
Overdoing it.

515
00:50:07,679 --> 00:50:10,186
Well, I think it's a case of, you know, personal experiment.

516
00:50:10,688 --> 00:50:11,532
I think you just have to...

517
00:50:12,434 --> 00:50:16,929
I mean, in terms of laziness...

518
00:50:17,855 --> 00:50:23,800
I like to just make, it's my own definition really, laziness is when you decide you're not going to do it.

519
00:50:24,621 --> 00:50:26,802
When you decide that instead you can have a cup of tea.

520
00:50:27,804 --> 00:50:29,246
It's actually a conscious decision.

521
00:50:30,146 --> 00:50:33,188
I'm fed up.

522
00:50:33,208 --> 00:50:39,534
Sloth and torpor are slightly more subtle because they're mental states that arise.

523
00:50:40,115 --> 00:50:44,739
And often we, my teacher used to call them our two very good friends.

524
00:50:45,277 --> 00:50:49,110
Because they're always saying, 10 minutes won't do you any harm.

525
00:50:49,130 --> 00:50:49,952
Just have a kip.

526
00:50:50,373 --> 00:50:52,179
You'll feel so good, you see.

527
00:50:52,661 --> 00:50:54,427
But in fact, it's not tiredness at all.

528
00:50:54,447 --> 00:50:56,333
It's just sloth and torpor.

529
00:50:59,789 --> 00:51:23,974
so in a sense you've got to experiment you've got to experiment you know and just be very aware of your body very aware of you know where the limits are when it came to Sloth and Torpor for instance and just general laziness and not want to do things this was the great problem of Moggallana who was the second great disciple of the Buddha and the Buddha gave him if I remember rightly 13 different ways

530
00:51:24,594 --> 00:51:28,259
to awaken, to sort of stay above the sloth and torpor.

531
00:51:28,519 --> 00:51:31,302
And only at the end of that could he say he was really tired and have a sleep.

532
00:51:32,423 --> 00:51:39,512
It's like you're trying to just push the boundary, but not so much that you crack it.

533
00:51:41,074 --> 00:51:45,199
And you have to be prepared to make mistakes.

534
00:51:45,219 --> 00:51:48,001
Unless you don't know the limit, you see, and then you make a mistake.

535
00:51:48,041 --> 00:51:50,485
But if you go warily, the mistake isn't crushing you.

536
00:51:52,625 --> 00:52:15,072
I'm just going back now to the 70s, the middle 70s, where so many people I know really got into this business of these insights, which are all delineated, and just exhausted themselves with this very wrong effort of trying to achieve something.

537
00:52:16,402 --> 00:52:20,005
And one very good friend of mine, he was in Burma actually, he dropped out.

538
00:52:20,065 --> 00:52:20,567
I could see it.

539
00:52:20,626 --> 00:52:21,427
I could see it happening.

540
00:52:22,148 --> 00:52:27,394
And he dropped out and I met him about seven years later and that year he'd spent £10,000 on crack.

541
00:52:29,117 --> 00:52:30,559
So you can fall a long way, you see.

542
00:52:31,659 --> 00:52:34,182
So that's not to frighten you.

543
00:52:34,222 --> 00:52:38,487
I'm not suggesting that you're going to rush out and get a crack at it.

544
00:52:39,670 --> 00:52:41,931
But it's just a matter of experimentation.

545
00:52:42,452 --> 00:52:43,353
It's just a matter of...

546
00:52:44,043 --> 00:52:46,947
working within your limits.

547
00:52:54,338 --> 00:52:57,664
May I say something?

548
00:52:57,684 --> 00:52:57,784
Sure.

549
00:52:57,804 --> 00:53:10,623
I work as a therapist in Canada and what I've found is that there's a tendency in Canada at least and perhaps over here as well for people to

550
00:53:11,009 --> 00:53:19,940
flog themselves very well and to really push quite hard.

551
00:53:19,960 --> 00:53:37,184
It's even quite inherent in the media telling us that we're not good enough, that we need to be better, look better, just something that we're not quite right.

552
00:53:37,704 --> 00:54:01,266
And that this can carry over into seeing that, for myself as well, that watching the pushing beyond and leaving to be the perfect meditator for myself and to be compassionate.
